{"title_page": "Kayleigh McEnany", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|White House Press Secretary}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Kayleigh McEnany\n|image       = Kayleigh McEnany (39645264535) (cropped).jpg\n|office      = 31st [[White House Press Secretary]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = April 7, 2020\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Stephanie Grisham]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|4|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sean Gilmartin]]|2017}}\n|children    = 1\n|education   = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Miami]]<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Kayleigh McEnany''' (born April 18, 1988)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/status/986625664534106114|title=Thank you to my incredible @GOP colleagues!!|date=April 18, 2018|website=Twitter}}</ref> is the [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]].<ref name=\"beast2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/23/meet-the-trumpkins-the-donald-s-army-of-media-hungry-cable-news-boosters.html|title=Meet the Trumpkins: The Donald's Army of Media-Hungry Cable News Boosters|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=February 22, 2016|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> A former [[CNN]] contributor, she was appointed national [[spokesperson]] for the [[Republican National Committee]] in 2017.<ref name=\"TWE\" /><ref name=\"RNC\" /> In February 2020, she was named national [[press secretary]] for [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-2020-campaign-announces-communication-team/2019/02/19/9b705318-344b-11e9-8375-e3dcf6b68558_story.html|title=Trump 2020 campaign announces communication team|last=|first=|date=February 19, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> On April 7, 2020, she was appointed White House press secretary.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Tampa, Florida]], McEnany is the daughter of commercial roofing company owner Michael McEnany and Leanne McEnany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/hillsborough/2019/10/31/kayleigh-mcenany-highlights-hillsborough-gop-lincoln-day-dinner/|title=Kayleigh McEnany highlights Hillsborough GOP Lincoln Day dinner|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=2019-10-31 |author1=March, William |accessdate=2020-01-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McEnany was educated at the [[Academy of the Holy Names (Florida)|Academy of the Holy Names]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/09/14/news_pf/Sports/Three_cheers_for_trad.shtml|title=Three cheers for tradition|work=SPTimes.com|author=Scott Purks|date=September 14, 2005|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> a Catholic [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in Tampa. After leaving school, she majored in international politics at [[Georgetown University]]'s [[School of Foreign Service]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref> [https://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator], Miami School of Law, 2 July 2014</ref> and then spent a year at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=Above/> After graduating from Georgetown, McEnany spent three years as a producer on the Mike Huckabee Show.<ref> [https://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator], Miami School of Law, 2 July 2014</ref>\n\nMcEnany enrolled at the University of Miami Law School, and then transferred to Harvard, where she graduated in 2016.<ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era], New York, Times, 27 April 2020</ref> According to the Miami School of Law, McEnany was the recipient of the [[Bruce Winick|Bruce J. Winick]] Award for Excellence, a scholarship awarded to students in the top 1% of their class.<ref name=\"Miami\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAs a college student, McEnany interned for several politicians, including [[Tom Gallagher]], [[Adam Putnam]], and [[George W. Bush]], and later worked in the [[White House Office of Communications]].<ref name=\"Miami\" /> After graduating from [[Georgetown University]], McEnany worked as a producer on [[Mike Huckabee]]'s eponymous television [[Huckabee|show]] and appeared on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"Miami\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator|title=From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator|website=law.miami.edu|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> Huckabee has said that \"one of the reasons [McEnany] went on to law school was because she didn\u2019t see she was going to have an on-air opportunity at Fox anytime soon.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\" />\n\n=== Media roles ===\nWhile in law school, she appeared on [[CNN]] and often defended President [[Donald Trump]], whom she supported in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref name=\"beast2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazza|first1=Ed|title=CNN Trump Surrogate Kayleigh McEnany Compares Miss Universe To Terror Suspect|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/kayleigh-mcenany-alicia-machado_us_57eb43e5e4b082aad9b7e643|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The Huffington Post|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"beast2\"/>\n\nOn August 5, 2017, McEnany left her position at CNN.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tornoe|first=Ron|title=Conservative pundit Kayleigh McEnany out at CNN|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/kayleigh-mcenany-cnn-trump-commentator-20170805.html|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 5, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref>  The following day, she hosted the webcast, ''[[Real News Update]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/kayleigh-mcenany-left-cnn-to-host-pro-trump-news-videos-2017-8|title=One of Trump's most vocal supporters left CNN to make a pro-Trump news video that's been compared to state TV|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|date=2017-08-07|work=Business Insider Australia|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en}}</ref> on Trump's personal Facebook page,<ref> [https://www.inquirer.com/philly/news/politics/presidential/out-at-cnn-kayleigh-mcenany-suddenly-appears-on-trumps-facebook-page-20170806.html Out at CNN, Kayleigh McEnany suddenly appears on Trump's Facebook page], The Philidelphia Enquiry, 6 August 2017</ref> in which she recapped all of Trump\u2019s accomplishments from the previous week.\n\nOn August 7, 2017, the [[Republican National Committee]] appointed McEnany as its national spokesperson.<ref name=TWE>{{cite news|last=Scarry|first=Eddie|title=Kayleigh McEnany joins Republican National Committee as spokesperson|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/kayleigh-mcenany-joins-republican-national-committee-as-spokesperson/article/2630829|accessdate=August 7, 2017|work=The Washington Examiner|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=RNC>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=gop.com |publisher=Republican National Committee |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Accepting her appointment, McEnany said in a press release, \"I am excited to be joining the RNC at such an important and historic time in our country. I'm eager to talk about Republican ideas and values and have important discussions about issues affecting Americans across this country.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=RNC Announcements |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer employer [[Mike Huckabee]] has called her a \"meticulous researcher\u201d and \"extraordinarily prepared.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\">{{cite web |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 May 2020}}</ref> Her rapid occupational success was noted by [[Van Jones]], CNN commentator and liberal activist who worked with  her at CNN, \"I\u2019m not trying to defend the messaging, but what I hope people can acknowledge is there's very few people in either party who can accomplish what Kayleigh has accomplished in such a short time... People keep taking her lightly, and they keep regretting it.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\"/>\n\n=== Role as Trump surrogate===\nAccording to the New York Times, McEnany saw Donald Trump as her ticket to stardom and began defending his actions in the media.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era], New York Times, 27 April 2020 </ref> Following Trump's lead, she criticised the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama presidency]]. In 2017, she mistakenly claimed that President Obama rushed off to a golf game after the 2002 beheading of [[Daniel Pearl]], though Obama was a state senator at the time of Pearl's murder. McEnany later apologized for the comment, noting that Obama went golfing after the 2014 murder of another journalist [[James Foley (journalist)|James Foley]] who was beheaded by ISIS in Syria. Obama, who was vacationing on [[Martha's Vineyard]] at the time, admitted that he should have \"anticipated the optics\" of golfing immediately after making a press statement on Foley's death.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tasneemnashrulla/obama-was-golfing-during-pearl-harbor This Trump Surrogate Accused Obama Of Golfing After Daniel Pearl's Murder \u2013 6 Years Before He Was Elected President], BuzzFeed News, 28 march 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Japaridze |first1=Nunu |title=Obama: Golfing after Foley statement was a bad idea |url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/09/07/politics/obama-golfing-optics/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nMcEnany is also alleged to have contributed to the racially charged and highly controversial \"[[birther]] movement\" by releasing [[Twitter|tweets]] that referenced President Obama's birth certificate and his half-brother [[Malik Obama]], who lives in [[Kenya]]. In one of them she wrote: \"How I Met Your Brother -- Never mind, forgot he's still in that hut in Kenya.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Betsy |title=Kayleigh McEnany set to become fourth Trump press secretary |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-new-white-house-press-secretary/index.html |website=CNN Politics |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Republican National Committee spokeswoman, she supported Trump in the aftermath of the 2017 conflict over Confederate General Lee's statue in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwood |first1=Max |title=RNC spokeswoman: GOP stands behind Trump's message 'of love and inclusiveness' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/346719-rnc-spokeswoman-the-gop-stands-behind-trumps-message-of-love-and-inclusiveness |website=The Hill |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the weeks prior to her appointment as White House press secretary, McEnany praised Trump's handling of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], saying, \"this president will always put America first, he will always protect American citizens,\" McEnany said<ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/kayleigh-mcenany-said-coronavirus-wouldnt-come-to-the-us-2020-4</ref>. \"We will not see diseases like the coronavirus come here, we will not see terrorism, and isn't that refreshing when contrasting it with the awful presidency of Barack Obama?\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=David|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/07/stephanie-grisham-out-as-trumps-press-secretary-after-never-briefing-the-press|title=Stephanie Grisham out as Trump press secretary after never briefing press|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the weeks following her remark, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|as the virus continued to spread]], McEnany was criticized by many for the comment. McEnany, in turn, claimed that she was only speaking in the context of restricting travel to the United States from China.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |last1=Wu |first1=Nicholas |title=New White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany takes heat for past comments on Obama, coronavirus |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/kayleigh-mcenanys-past-comments-obama-coronavirus/2968413001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===White House Press Secretary===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49842842006).jpg|thumb|right|McEnany at a press conference in May 2020]]\nAfter [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] replaced [[Mick Mulvaney]] as White House Chief of Staff in April 2020, Meadows' first personnel change was hiring McEnany as White House Press Secretary on April 7, 2020; which was officially announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singman |first=Brooke |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-names-campaign-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-as-new-white-house-press-secretary |title=Trump names campaign spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany as new White House press secretary |date=April 8, 2020 |work=Fox News |access-date=April 17, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |last2=Cates |first2=Christopher J |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Stephanie Grisham]], who had served in the role and as [[White House Communications Director]] since June 2019, became [[Melania Trump]]'s chief of staff and spokesperson.<ref>Phillips, Morgan (April 7, 2020). [https://www.foxnews.com/politics/who-is-kayleigh-mcenany-what-to-know-about-incoming-white-house-press-secretary Who is Kayleigh McEnany? What to know about incoming White House press secretary]. ''[[Fox News]]''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref>\n\nMcEnany backed up Trump's assertion that the [[World Health Organization]] had shown a \"clear bias towards China.\" She claimed the WHO put Americans at risk by \"repeating inaccurate claims peddled by China during the coronavirus pandemic\" and \"opposing the United States' life-saving travel restrictions.\"<ref>[https://www.stuff.co.nz/world/americas/121286785/trump-expands-battle-with-who Trump expands battle with WHO], Stuff, 26 April 2020</ref>\n\nWhen Trump was criticized for suggesting that disinfectant could be used in people to kill the coronavirus, McEnany said that the President's remarks were simply taken out of context.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/26/politics/trump-briefings-media-blame-disinfectant-comments/index.html An aggrieved Trump blames the press for furor over disinfectant comments as Birx defends him,] CNN 26 April 2020 </ref>\n\nIn her first public press briefing on 1 May, 2020, McEnany was asked by an Associated Press reporter: \u201cWill you pledge to never lie to us from that podium?\u201d Without hesitation, McEnany replied: \u201cI will never lie to you. You have my word on that.\u201d  On the subject of Trump\u2019s responses to the coronavirus pandemic (in the same briefing), she then claimed: \u201cThis president has always sided on the side of data\u201d. In response to allegations of Trump's sexual misconduct, she said: \u201cHe has always told the truth\u201d.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/may/01/trump-lie-kayleigh-mcenany-press-secretary-coronavrius-michael-flynn Trump 'cannot tell a lie' \u2013 but can Kayleigh McEnany, his new press secretary?] The Guardian, 1 May 2020 </ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcEnany married [[Sean Gilmartin]], a professional [[pitcher|baseball pitcher]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] organization, in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rays' Sean Gilmartin: Gets camp invite with Rays |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1941508/sean-gilmartin |website=CBS Sports |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/ex-met-sean-gilmartin-marries-rnc-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-article-1.3647275|title=Former Mets pitcher Sean Gilmartin marries RNC spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany|website=New York Daily News |author1=Ripple, Zachary|date=2017-11-20 |accessdate=2018-01-08|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The couple has one daughter, Blake, born November 2019.<ref>https://heavy.com/news/2020/04/sean-gilmartin-kayleigh-mcenany-husband/</ref><ref>https://www.tampabay.com/sports/rays/2020/03/03/rays-power-couple-one-pitches-strikes-the-other-pitches-donald-trump/</ref> \n\nMcEnany is Christian.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Marc |last=Topkin |authorlink=   |title= Rays power couple: One pitches strikes, the other pitches Donald Trump  |newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/rays/2020/03/03/rays-power-couple-one-pitches-strikes-the-other-pitches-donald-trump/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The New American Revolution: The Making of a Populist Movement'' (2018)<ref name=\"FoxNewsMcEnanyBook\">{{cite web |url= http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/07/michael-wolff-wasn-t-with-trump-on-election-night-those-who-were-prove-his-book-wrong.html |title= Michael Wolff wasn't with Trump on election night. Those who were prove his book wrong |author= Kayleigh McEnany |date= January 8, 2018 |work= [[Fox News]] |accessdate= January 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27733823|c=Category:Kayleigh McEnany|q=Kayleigh McEnany|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n* [https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/ Twitter]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephanie Grisham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secretary]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n\n{{WHPS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McEnany, Kayleigh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:Christians from Florida]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Political spokespersons]]\n[[Category:School of Foreign Service alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Press Secretaries]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tampa, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|White House Press Secretary}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Kayleigh McEnany\n|image       = Kayleigh McEnany (39645264535) (cropped).jpg\n|office      = 31st [[White House Press Secretary]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = April 7, 2020\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Stephanie Grisham]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|4|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sean Gilmartin]]|2017}}\n|children    = 1\n|education   = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Miami]]<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Kayleigh McEnany''' (born April 18, 1988)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/status/986625664534106114|title=Thank you to my incredible @GOP colleagues!!|date=April 18, 2018|website=Twitter}}</ref> is the [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]].<ref name=\"beast2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/23/meet-the-trumpkins-the-donald-s-army-of-media-hungry-cable-news-boosters.html|title=Meet the Trumpkins: The Donald's Army of Media-Hungry Cable News Boosters|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=February 22, 2016|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> A former [[CNN]] contributor, she was appointed national [[spokesperson]] for the [[Republican National Committee]] in 2017.<ref name=\"TWE\" /><ref name=\"RNC\" /> In February 2020, she was named national [[press secretary]] for [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-2020-campaign-announces-communication-team/2019/02/19/9b705318-344b-11e9-8375-e3dcf6b68558_story.html|title=Trump 2020 campaign announces communication team|last=|first=|date=February 19, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> On April 7, 2020, she was appointed White House press secretary.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Tampa, Florida]], McEnany is the daughter of commercial roofing company owner Michael McEnany and Leanne McEnany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/hillsborough/2019/10/31/kayleigh-mcenany-highlights-hillsborough-gop-lincoln-day-dinner/|title=Kayleigh McEnany highlights Hillsborough GOP Lincoln Day dinner|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=2019-10-31 |author1=March, William |accessdate=2020-01-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McEnany was educated at the [[Academy of the Holy Names (Florida)|Academy of the Holy Names]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/09/14/news_pf/Sports/Three_cheers_for_trad.shtml|title=Three cheers for tradition|work=SPTimes.com|author=Scott Purks|date=September 14, 2005|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> a Catholic [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in Tampa. After leaving school, she majored in international politics at [[Georgetown University]]'s [[School of Foreign Service]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref> [https://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator], Miami School of Law, 2 July 2014</ref> and then spent a year at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=Above/> After graduating from Georgetown, McEnany spent three years as a producer on the Mike Huckabee Show.<ref> [https://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator], Miami School of Law, 2 July 2014</ref>\n\nMcEnany enrolled at the University of Miami Law School, and then transferred to Harvard, where she graduated in 2016.<ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era], New York, Times, 27 April 2020</ref> According to the Miami School of Law, McEnany was the recipient of the [[Bruce Winick|Bruce J. Winick]] Award for Excellence, a scholarship awarded to students in the top 1% of their class.<ref name=\"Miami\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAs a college student, McEnany interned for several politicians including [[Tom Gallagher]], [[Adam Putnam]], and [[George W. Bush]], and later worked in the [[White House Office of Communications]].<ref name=\"Miami\" /> After graduating from [[Georgetown University]], McEnany worked as a producer on [[Mike Huckabee]]'s eponymous television [[Huckabee|show]] and appeared on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"Miami\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator|title=From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator|website=law.miami.edu|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> Huckabee has said that \"one of the reasons [McEnany] went on to law school was because she didn\u2019t see she was going to have an on-air opportunity at Fox anytime soon.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\" />\n\n=== Media roles ===\nWhile in law school, she appeared on [[CNN]] and often defended President [[Donald Trump]], whom she supported in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref name=\"beast2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazza|first1=Ed|title=CNN Trump Surrogate Kayleigh McEnany Compares Miss Universe To Terror Suspect|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/kayleigh-mcenany-alicia-machado_us_57eb43e5e4b082aad9b7e643|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The Huffington Post|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"beast2\"/>\n\nOn August 5, 2017, McEnany left her position at CNN.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tornoe|first=Ron|title=Conservative pundit Kayleigh McEnany out at CNN|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/kayleigh-mcenany-cnn-trump-commentator-20170805.html|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 5, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref>  The following day, she hosted the webcast, ''[[Real News Update]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/kayleigh-mcenany-left-cnn-to-host-pro-trump-news-videos-2017-8|title=One of Trump's most vocal supporters left CNN to make a pro-Trump news video that's been compared to state TV|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|date=2017-08-07|work=Business Insider Australia|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en}}</ref> on Trump's personal Facebook page,<ref> [https://www.inquirer.com/philly/news/politics/presidential/out-at-cnn-kayleigh-mcenany-suddenly-appears-on-trumps-facebook-page-20170806.html Out at CNN, Kayleigh McEnany suddenly appears on Trump's Facebook page], The Philidelphia Enquiry, 6 August 2017</ref> in which she recapped all of Trump\u2019s accomplishments from the previous week.\n\nOn August 7, 2017, the [[Republican National Committee]] appointed McEnany as its national spokesperson.<ref name=TWE>{{cite news|last=Scarry|first=Eddie|title=Kayleigh McEnany joins Republican National Committee as spokesperson|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/kayleigh-mcenany-joins-republican-national-committee-as-spokesperson/article/2630829|accessdate=August 7, 2017|work=The Washington Examiner|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=RNC>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=gop.com |publisher=Republican National Committee |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Accepting her appointment, McEnany said in a press release, \"I am excited to be joining the RNC at such an important and historic time in our country. I'm eager to talk about Republican ideas and values and have important discussions about issues affecting Americans across this country.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=RNC Announcements |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer employer [[Mike Huckabee]] has called her a \"meticulous researcher\u201d and \"extraordinarily prepared.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\">{{cite web |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 May 2020}}</ref> Her rapid occupational success was noted by [[Van Jones]], CNN commentator and liberal activist who worked with  her at CNN, \"I\u2019m not trying to defend the messaging, but what I hope people can acknowledge is there's very few people in either party who can accomplish what Kayleigh has accomplished in such a short time... People keep taking her lightly, and they keep regretting it.\"<ref name=\"Williamson\"/>\n\n=== Role as Trump surrogate===\nAccording to the New York Times, McEnany saw Donald Trump as her ticket to stardom and began defending his actions in the media.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/27/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-coronavirus.html In Kayleigh McEnany, Trump Taps a Press Fighter for the Coronavirus Era], New York Times, 27 April 2020 </ref> Following Trump's lead, she criticised the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama presidency]]. In 2017, she mistakenly claimed that President Obama rushed off to a golf game after the 2002 beheading of [[Daniel Pearl]], though Obama was a state senator at the time of Pearl's murder. McEnany later apologized for the comment, noting that Obama went golfing after the 2014 murder of another journalist [[James Foley (journalist)|James Foley]] who was beheaded by ISIS in Syria. Obama, who was vacationing on [[Martha's Vineyard]] at the time, admitted that he should have \"anticipated the optics\" of golfing immediately after making a press statement on Foley's death.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tasneemnashrulla/obama-was-golfing-during-pearl-harbor This Trump Surrogate Accused Obama Of Golfing After Daniel Pearl's Murder \u2013 6 Years Before He Was Elected President], BuzzFeed News, 28 march 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Japaridze |first1=Nunu |title=Obama: Golfing after Foley statement was a bad idea |url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/09/07/politics/obama-golfing-optics/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nMcEnany is also alleged to have contributed to the racially charged and highly controversial \"[[birther]] movement\" by releasing [[Twitter|tweets]] that referenced President Obama's birth certificate and his half-brother [[Malik Obama]], who lives in [[Kenya]]. In one of them she wrote: \"How I Met Your Brother -- Never mind, forgot he's still in that hut in Kenya.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Betsy |title=Kayleigh McEnany set to become fourth Trump press secretary |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-new-white-house-press-secretary/index.html |website=CNN Politics |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Republican National Committee spokeswoman, she supported Trump in the aftermath of the 2017 conflict over Confederate General Lee's statue in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwood |first1=Max |title=RNC spokeswoman: GOP stands behind Trump's message 'of love and inclusiveness' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/346719-rnc-spokeswoman-the-gop-stands-behind-trumps-message-of-love-and-inclusiveness |website=The Hill |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the weeks prior to her appointment as White House press secretary, McEnany praised Trump's handling of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], saying, \"this president will always put America first, he will always protect American citizens,\" McEnany said<ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/kayleigh-mcenany-said-coronavirus-wouldnt-come-to-the-us-2020-4</ref>. \"We will not see diseases like the coronavirus come here, we will not see terrorism, and isn't that refreshing when contrasting it with the awful presidency of Barack Obama?\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=David|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/07/stephanie-grisham-out-as-trumps-press-secretary-after-never-briefing-the-press|title=Stephanie Grisham out as Trump press secretary after never briefing press|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the weeks following her remark, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|as the virus continued to spread]], McEnany was criticized by many for the comment. McEnany, in turn, claimed that she was only speaking in the context of restricting travel to the United States from China.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |last1=Wu |first1=Nicholas |title=New White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany takes heat for past comments on Obama, coronavirus |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/kayleigh-mcenanys-past-comments-obama-coronavirus/2968413001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===White House Press Secretary===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49842842006).jpg|thumb|right|McEnany at a press conference in May 2020]]\nAfter [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] replaced [[Mick Mulvaney]] as White House Chief of Staff in April 2020, Meadows' first personnel change was hiring McEnany as White House Press Secretary on April 7, 2020; which was officially announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singman |first=Brooke |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-names-campaign-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-as-new-white-house-press-secretary |title=Trump names campaign spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany as new White House press secretary |date=April 8, 2020 |work=Fox News |access-date=April 17, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |last2=Cates |first2=Christopher J |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Stephanie Grisham]], who had served in the role and as [[White House Communications Director]] since June 2019, became [[Melania Trump]]'s chief of staff and spokesperson.<ref>Phillips, Morgan (April 7, 2020). [https://www.foxnews.com/politics/who-is-kayleigh-mcenany-what-to-know-about-incoming-white-house-press-secretary Who is Kayleigh McEnany? What to know about incoming White House press secretary]. ''[[Fox News]]''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref>\n\nMcEnany backed up Trump's assertion that the [[World Health Organization]] had shown a \"clear bias towards China.\" She claimed the WHO put Americans at risk by \"repeating inaccurate claims peddled by China during the coronavirus pandemic\" and \"opposing the United States' life-saving travel restrictions.\"<ref>[https://www.stuff.co.nz/world/americas/121286785/trump-expands-battle-with-who Trump expands battle with WHO], Stuff, 26 April 2020</ref>\n\nWhen Trump was criticized for suggesting that disinfectant could be used in people to kill the coronavirus, McEnany said that the President's remarks were simply taken out of context.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/26/politics/trump-briefings-media-blame-disinfectant-comments/index.html An aggrieved Trump blames the press for furor over disinfectant comments as Birx defends him,] CNN 26 April 2020 </ref>\n\nIn her first public press briefing on 1 May, 2020, McEnany was asked by an Associated Press reporter: \u201cWill you pledge to never lie to us from that podium?\u201d Without hesitation, McEnany replied: \u201cI will never lie to you. You have my word on that.\u201d  On the subject of Trump\u2019s responses to the coronavirus pandemic (in the same briefing), she then claimed: \u201cThis president has always sided on the side of data\u201d. In response to allegations of Trump's sexual misconduct, she said: \u201cHe has always told the truth\u201d.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/may/01/trump-lie-kayleigh-mcenany-press-secretary-coronavrius-michael-flynn Trump 'cannot tell a lie' \u2013 but can Kayleigh McEnany, his new press secretary?] The Guardian, 1 May 2020 </ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcEnany married [[Sean Gilmartin]], a professional [[pitcher|baseball pitcher]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] organization, in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rays' Sean Gilmartin: Gets camp invite with Rays |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1941508/sean-gilmartin |website=CBS Sports |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/ex-met-sean-gilmartin-marries-rnc-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-article-1.3647275|title=Former Mets pitcher Sean Gilmartin marries RNC spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany|website=New York Daily News |author1=Ripple, Zachary|date=2017-11-20 |accessdate=2018-01-08|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The couple has one daughter, Blake, born November 2019.<ref>https://heavy.com/news/2020/04/sean-gilmartin-kayleigh-mcenany-husband/</ref><ref>https://www.tampabay.com/sports/rays/2020/03/03/rays-power-couple-one-pitches-strikes-the-other-pitches-donald-trump/</ref> \n\nMcEnany is Christian.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Marc |last=Topkin |authorlink=   |title= Rays power couple: One pitches strikes, the other pitches Donald Trump  |newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/rays/2020/03/03/rays-power-couple-one-pitches-strikes-the-other-pitches-donald-trump/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The New American Revolution: The Making of a Populist Movement'' (2018)<ref name=\"FoxNewsMcEnanyBook\">{{cite web |url= http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/07/michael-wolff-wasn-t-with-trump-on-election-night-those-who-were-prove-his-book-wrong.html |title= Michael Wolff wasn't with Trump on election night. Those who were prove his book wrong |author= Kayleigh McEnany |date= January 8, 2018 |work= [[Fox News]] |accessdate= January 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27733823|c=Category:Kayleigh McEnany|q=Kayleigh McEnany|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n* [https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/ Twitter]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephanie Grisham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secre